{"questionId":"22166307","questionHtml":"<p>The cross section of the side of a building can be modelled by a curve with equation <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>43</mn></math> , as shown in the following diagram. Distances are measured in metres.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/b7c4f89b68f2cef393837afe0e75b5f35b922a3b.png\" width=\"736\" height=\"423\"></p>\n<p>A builder leans a straight ladder against the building to do repairs. For safety reasons, the angle between the ladder and the horizontal ground must be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>75</mn><mo>°</mo></math>.<br><br>Find the height above the ground at which the ladder touches the building.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt to find gradient&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>EITHER</strong></p>\n<p>gradient of tangent <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>tan</mi><mo> </mo><mn>75</mn><mo>°</mo><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>73205</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>A1</strong></em> for negative and <em><strong>A1</strong></em> for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>tan</mi><mo> </mo><mn>75</mn><mo>°</mo></math> (or equivalent).<br><br></p>\n<p><strong>OR</strong></p>\n<p>gradient of tangent <em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>tan</mi><mo> </mo><mn>105</mn><mo>°</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>73205</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (A2)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>THEN</strong></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>y</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em> for a labelled sketch of the derivative function.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>equating derivative to their gradient&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <strong><em>(M1)</em></strong></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>73205</mn><mo>…</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo></math> &nbsp;<strong>OR&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong> line on graph<br><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>677993</mn><mo>…</mo></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <strong><em>(A1)(M1)A0</em></strong> for an answer of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>38</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn></math>, from calculator being in degrees.</p>\n<p>Award <em><strong>A0M1A0</strong></em> if “<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mi>x</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>73205</mn><mo>…</mo></math>” seen, but leading to an incorrect <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-value.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>height<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>677993</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>67</mn><mo> </mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mfenced><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>67274</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; A1</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:right;\"><em><strong>[8 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22166307","referenceCode":"24M.1.AHL.TZ1.16","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"The cross section of the side of a building can be modelled by a curve with equation y=5 cos 1.1x, 0≤x≤1.43 , as shown in the following diagram. Distances are measured in metres. A","paper":"1","level":"AHL","questionNumber":"16","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 8]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.4—Tangents and normal","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.9—Differentiating standard functions and derivative rules","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.1—Equations of straight lines, parallel and perpendicular"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}}}